   <titles>
      <title>Series: Examples</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Constant series</strong>   For any <math>
                     <latex>a\in\RNr</latex>
                  </math>, the constant series with summands equal to <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> is
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>constant</term>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Introduction of the concept.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <term>constant</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Introduction of the concept.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>a+a+a+\cdots + a+\cdots = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} a_n</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>where <math>
                     <latex>a_n:=a</latex>
                  </math> for all <math>
                     <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                  </math>. – For example, the choice <math>
                     <latex>a:=1</latex>
                  </math> yields the constant series</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>1+1+1+\cdots + 1+\cdots</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Harmonic series</strong>   The harmonic series is
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>harmonic</term>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The harmonic series is</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \cdots + \dfrac{1}{n} + \cdots \ =\ \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{n}</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <term>harmonic</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The harmonic series is</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \cdots + \dfrac{1}{n} + \cdots \ =\ \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{n}</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \cdots + \dfrac{1}{n} + \cdots \ =\ \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{n}</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Geometric series</strong>   The geometric series associated to <math>
                     <latex>r\neq 0</latex>
                  </math> is
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>geometric</term>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The geometric series associated to <math>
                              <latex>r\neq 0</latex>
                           </math> is</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n + \cdots\ =\ \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} r^n</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <term>geometric</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The geometric series associated to <math>
                              <latex>r\neq 0</latex>
                           </math> is</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n + \cdots\ =\ \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} r^n</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n + \cdots\ =\ \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} r^n</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>For example, <math>
                     <latex>r=1/2</latex>
                  </math> yields the geometric series</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{8} + \cdots + \dfrac{1}{2^n}+\cdots \ =\ \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{2^n}</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>For example, <math>
                     <latex>r=-3</latex>
                  </math> yields the geometric series</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>1 + -3 + 9 - 27 + \cdots + (-3)^n +\cdots \ =\ \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-3)^n</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
